A '''big bang''' project is one that has no staged delivery. The customer must wait, sometimes months, before seeing anything from the development team. At the end of the wait comes a "big bang". A common argument against big bang projects is that there are no check points during the project where the customers expectations can be tested, thus risking that the final delivery is not what the customer had in mind.

This concept is used frequently in [[extreme programming]].


